Reformation shaped everyday lives, it was also profoundly shaped by them in turn. England became a Protestant nation not in spite of its people but through their active social, political, and religious participation in creating a new church in England.A People’s Reformation explores this world from the pews, reimagining the lived experience and fierce negotiation of church and state in the parishes of Elizabethan England. It places ordinary people at the centre of the local, cultural, and political history of the Reformation and its remarkable, transformative effect on the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChurch and statezEnglandxHistoryy16th century. 0aReformationzEngland. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / Stuart Era (1603-1714).2bisacsh  aAnglican.  aBook.  aCatholicism.  aCommon.  aEaster.  aElizabeth.  aEngland.  aHenry VIII.  aLondon.  aNorwich.  aParliament.  aPrayer.  aPresbyterian.  aProtestant.  aProtestantism.  aTudor.  aYorkshire.  aaccounts.  aagrarian.  aarchitecture.  aarchival.  aarchives.  achurchwarden.  aclass.  aclergy.  aclerical.  acommunion.  acommunity.  aculture.  aeconomics.  aeucharist.  aeveryday.  aformation.  agender.  ahistory.  alaity.  alayman.  alife.  amaterial.  amicroeconomics.  anonconformist.  aofficeholding.  apenance.  apews.  apolitics.  apoor.  apopular.  apower.  arecusant.  arelief.  asacrament.  asermon.  asocial.  asociology.  astate.  astudies.  asurveillance.  ataxation.  atithes.  aurban.  avisitation.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228017745?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228017745423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228017745/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles